# Cursor Pointer on Interactive Elements

All clickable elements (links, buttons, logo/home that navigates) must show `cursor: pointer` on hover so users see they are interactive.

## Rules

- **Native `<button>`**: Add `cursor-pointer` to the className (or ensure your shared `Button` component includes it in its base styles).
- **`<a>` or Next.js `<Link>`**: Add `cursor-pointer` if your global styles don’t already give links a pointer cursor.
- **Clickable non-button elements** (e.g. `<span>` or `<div>` with `onClick`, or wrapper around logo that navigates): Always add `cursor-pointer`.
- **Shared components**: Prefer adding `cursor-pointer` in the base component (e.g. `Button`) so all usages get it.

## Examples

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD – button has cursor-pointer (in base class or here)
<button type="button" className="cursor-pointer ..." onClick={...}>
  Sign up
</button>

// ✅ GOOD – Link with explicit pointer
<Link href="/login" className="cursor-pointer ...">
  Log in
</Link>

// ✅ GOOD – clickable non-button
<span className="cursor-pointer ..." onClick={onLogoClick} role="button">
  Logo
</span>

// ❌ BAD – clickable element without pointer
<button type="button" className="rounded-full px-5 ..." onClick={...}>
  Sign up
</button>
```

## Checklist

When adding or editing a link or button:

- [ ] Element has `cursor-pointer` (Tailwind) or `cursor: pointer` (CSS).
- [ ] If it’s a shared `Button`/link component, the base styles include the pointer cursor.
